00:00:01.100 --> 00:00:06.900
So c, little c, the speed of light, probably one of the most famous symbols in physics.

00:00:07.000 --> 00:00:11.400
Certainly it appears in the most famous equation: E=m c squared

00:00:11.500 --> 00:00:18.500
The c in there is the speed of light.
It really is one of the most fundamental constants.

00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:24.700
- c, small c, means the speed of light.

00:00:24.800 --> 00:00:29.900
That's what, three times ten to the eighth metres per second.

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:34.400
So three hunderd million meters per second. So it's fast, but not infinitly fast.

00:00:34.500 --> 00:00:37.900
- It really is the ultimate constant in physics.

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:41.800
In the sense that it really is the same, whoever measures it.

00:00:41.900 --> 00:00:44.550
That's what lies at the heart of special relativity,

00:00:44.650 --> 00:00:47.600
this idea that the universe is a relative sort of place.

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:51.600
One of the precepts of special relativity is that the laws of physics

00:00:51.700 --> 00:00:55.100
are the same in any reference frame, if you're stationary or moving

00:00:55.200 --> 00:00:57.200
you should see the same laws of physics.

00:00:57.300 --> 00:00:59.700
- Why is the speed of light c?

00:00:59.800 --> 00:01:04.500
- Why is it said to be c or called c? That I don't know.

00:01:04.600 --> 00:01:11.800
I really don't know why that constant has been defined as being called c.

00:01:11.900 --> 00:01:14.900
I'd be interested to know if Mike knows.

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:19.500
- Maybe because it is thought to be a fundamental constant.

00:01:19.600 --> 00:01:22.600
c for constant, but I don't really know.

00:01:25.100 --> 00:01:27.700
- People are kind-of used to the idea that speeds add.

00:01:27.800 --> 00:01:31.500
So that if you see an aircraft taking off from an aircraft carrier,

00:01:31.600 --> 00:01:34.600
if you want to know how fast the aircraft is going,

00:01:34.700 --> 00:01:38.400
you have to add how fast the aircraft is moving relative to the aircraft carrier,

00:01:38.500 --> 00:01:42.400
to how fast that was moving forward, so the total speed is the sum of the two.

00:01:42.500 --> 00:01:46.500
People are very used to that and you use that kind of calculations,

00:01:46.600 --> 00:01:49.000
eg. to calculate how fast a car is coming towards you.

00:01:49.100 --> 00:01:51.000
You're measuring realtive speeds of things.

00:01:51.100 --> 00:01:56.200
But the weird thing about light is, because the speed is always the same, it doesn't add in that way.

00:01:56.300 --> 00:02:00.500
So if you're moving in a train and shine a flashlight from the train,

00:02:00.600 --> 00:02:03.700
and you measure the speed that the light comes out of the flashlight at,

00:02:03.800 --> 00:02:07.100
it comes out at exactly the same speed as if you weren't on the train.

00:02:07.200 --> 00:02:10.800
So, speeds don't add. The speed of light, whoever measures it,

00:02:10.900 --> 00:02:14.500
however you produce the light, always is the same value, c.

00:02:14.800 --> 00:02:17.600
That's not quite true, that's the speed of light in a vacuum.

00:02:17.700 --> 00:02:20.100
There are ways to slow light down.

00:02:21.800 --> 00:02:24.500
If light travels through air it travels a little more slowly.

00:02:24.600 --> 00:02:27.800
It can never go faster than in a vacuum, you can make it slow down.

00:02:27.900 --> 00:02:32.900
People will do sophisticated experiments in a laboratory, to slow down light to a snails pace,

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:36.000
by messing around with the refractive index of a material.

00:02:36.100 --> 00:02:39.200
Messing around with the properties of the material it is propagating through.

00:02:39.300 --> 00:02:43.500
You can make it slow down, you can never exceed the speed that it goes in a vacuum.

00:02:43.600 --> 00:02:47.300
So c is in that sense a cosmic speed limit, it it the fastest there is.

00:02:47.800 --> 00:02:51.900
