For most of the experiments we do in this lab, we're looking at electrons in semiconductors

00:03:08.900 --> 00:03:14.100
which are moving well below the speed of light, typically about one hunderdth of the speed of light.

00:03:14.200 --> 00:03:16.300
- How do we measure the speed of light?

00:03:16.400 --> 00:03:21.900
- It's a quite difficult thing to measure, for a long time the experiments were quite crude

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:24.900
and the constraint we had on the speed of light were quite limited.

00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:29.300
Some of the best measurements we have today are by using radar echos off things.

00:03:29.400 --> 00:03:32.800
You can bounce a radarbeam of things, because it is called the speed of light,

00:03:32.900 --> 00:03:35.900
but ofcourse all the electromagnetic waves travel at the same speed.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:40.400
If it is a radio wave, an x-ray, optical light it all travels at the same speed.

00:03:40.500 --> 00:03:44.400
By bouncing radio waves off things, we can measure the speed pretty accurately.

00:03:48.200 --> 00:03:52.300
Because light travels extremely fast, 3 times 10 to the eighth metres per second,

00:03:52.400 --> 00:03:55.400
that's 300 million metres every second light travels at.

00:03:55.500 --> 00:04:00.300
Obviously you can't sit there with a stop-watch and measure it that way, it's too fast.

00:04:00.400 --> 00:04:03.400
Unless you can find something that's a long way away.

00:04:03.500 --> 00:04:07.800
So bouncing light off the moon or other planets is by using strong radar signals,

00:04:07.900 --> 00:04:10.400
is a very good way of measuring how fast that light's going.

